      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Race for No. 2: A Debate With a Difference</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Martin E Cobern letter, commenting on October 6 article on vice presidential debate between Democrat Sen Joseph I Lieberman and Republican rival Dick Cheney, disputes Chewney's assertions about source of his personal wealth</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>One of the more bizarre statements in Thursday night's vice-presidential debate was Dick Cheney's assertion that the government had mostly nothing to do with his recent financial success (front page, Oct. 6). In fact, the government had everything to do with it!</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>One of the more bizarre statements in Thursday night's vice-presidential debate was Dick Cheney's assertion that the government had mostly nothing to do with his recent financial success (front page, Oct. 6). In fact, the government had everything to do with it!</p>
        <p>Does Mr. Cheney, a former defense secretary, think he got the chairmanship at Halliburton on the basis of his proven corporate management expertise? Or was it more for the contacts in the United States  and in foreign governments that he developed in his years on the federal payroll?</p>
        <p>These connections have paid off handsomely for Mr. Cheney and for his company.</p>
        <p>MARTIN E. COBERN  Cheshire, Conn., Oct. 6, 2000</p>
      </block>
